The desert Southwest is a weird and wonderful place. It’s always worth a visit but sometimes it just flat out over-delivers, with imagery that will have you wondering what planet you’re on. 

This was one of those times. January 1, 2020. I’d been blessed with epic skies since December 23, 2019, shooting those electric sky images at the Desert Air motel in Sanderson Texas. The next sunset in Las Cruces? Same thing. Beautiful Technicolor sunset. And on to Tucson. Somehow, nearly a week later, it happened again. Looking west, the sky was OK. Not the best sunset ever but not bad. It was when I turned around and saw what was starting to happen, that’s when I knew I had to quit screwing around and get the Velvia 100 loaded GW690III out. The sunlight was being filtered through clouds to the west, and the mountains cut the light to perfection. 

This was the last shot on the roll. Underexposed a stop cause I was losing light fast, but did not wanna blow the neon out. All I did in post was a curves tweak to lift shadows. 📺💣⚛️Vision3 500T plus Canon T70 plus 50mm f/1.8

If you want to walk around after dark pretending your nearly 40 year old film camera is a brand new digital camera, this isn’t a bad way to go. I’ve done it before just to see if it would work and I got away with a lot more than I should have gotten away with. So I did it again in Tucumcari back in October. 

Why’d I shoot film when I had two state of the art digitals and an iPhone 14 pro max in my arsenal? Because! That’s why. What’s the challenge in shooting these things digitally? Let’s make it messy and inconvenient. All for art’s sake! IDK. There is reward in pushing old tech to the redline. Making it reach for the edge of what it can do. And the colors! Kodak Vision3 is a tungsten balanced film. So the blue cast that screams “night shot” comes free of charge. Vision3 is essentially Cinestill 800T, without the halation (those red halos around highlights) and spotty availability. It does come with remjet, which requires some extra futzing. I shoot film. I’m an engineer. Futzing is in my DNA🤓.

TLDR: it’s AGFA Aviphot Chrome. 

Call it Rollei CR200. Crossbird. Lomo Peacock. I’ve enjoyed this film under all those names. In every format from 110 to 127.

When developed in E6 as a transparency, the images have a deep aqua base tint which transitions to magenta as the exposure values approach 18%. Brighter details shift to warm yellow. Split toning, all done in chemistry. 

Cross processed in C41 I get stunning purple negatives which #negativelabpro inverts to a riot of teal and orange. There is *nothing* else like this film. 

Turns out it was last made in 2005. I discovered it as Lomo Peacock in 2012. Then, as Rollei CR200. Origin rumors surrounded this film, chief among them that it was a Belgian made derivative of AGFA RSX, a beautiful and well respected transparency film from grand old AGFA. Except: no. I have some original AGFA RSX in the consumer version: 2000 vintage Precisa CT100. Examples are in my feed. Even 20 years after its expiration date it looks beautiful. And not a bit like CR200.

The films are radically dissimilar.  One rumor was that the CR films originated from a contaminated batch of late production RSX. Wait. One of my favorite films was the spawn of an industrial accident? Hard NO.  I refused to believe it. My best argument against the single batch origin was that during the 2010s the film sold out every year, reappearing the next year with expiry dates incremented. So, that’s proof, right? We can’t be carrion eaters picking film off a carcass, right? RIGHT? Err….Hold that thought. 

Last week I shared LaMesa Motel on this stock with dev in E6. In that post I mentioned finding what appears to be the definitive back story of this beautiful oddity. Swipe to see the words of one Henning Serger, whose Photrio née APUG posts appear authentic, with no one challenging their accuracy. Especially, note where he states it is industry practice to manufacture mass quantities of a given stock before switching the line to another product, banking a “lifetime” supply of mother rolls in cold storage (continued in the comments)…

More from that roll of Vision3 500T shot hand-held in a vintage Canon T70.

Developed in the kitchen sink using DIY ECN-2 mixed up from raw chemicals. The neon colors captured by this film are about as close to perfect as any film/developer combo is likely to give. Look closely at the true neon next time you see a photo of a neon sign. The spectra of neon gas has plenty of red and deep red. But there’s also a lot of area under the curve in the yellows and greens, too. In person the reddish orange tones dominate. When that neon light hits a sensor or a piece of film trouble starts. The red channel approaches saturation. That has the effect of raising the green channel relative to red. And that hypnotizing neon glow is rendered the same ghastly shade of yellow as those bottles of Plochman’s mustard found at the Nevada nuke test site years after the test bans. Before you ask which bottles of Plochman’s, be aware that I frequently make sh🤠t up on the fly. But photos of neon *do* often render reddish orange neon as a ghastly sick yellow. 🌞

Ira’s Bar * Nara Visa NM * Eastman Kodak Vision3 500T cinema film * Kitchen Sink DIY ECN-2 

Following this road into Missouri would take you right to my home town. I think they’re up to three whole traffic lights now! Nara Visa is a town which holds a dim childhood memory for me: my grandmother, laid to rest in the National Cemetery one can see on the hill when leaving Santa Fe northbound on US-285, passed away in October 1970. I was six. I remember my uncle coming down from Tonganoxie KS in his 1969 Caprice, a loaded 427 car. He met dad and I in Ft. Scott, as we came in from El Dorado Springs MO to meet up with him. Dad’s truck was left in Ft. Scott and we headed to Santa Fe for my grandmother’s funeral. I remember waking up to what looked like an alien landscape to my Missouri Ozarks eyes. Dad was driving, and talking to my uncle about how dim the car’s headlights were. The alternator belt had been slipping for miles, spinning hard enough to keep the idiot light off but not enough to keep up with the load on the electrical system. The belt finally failed on the stretch of 54 in the picture. I remember rolling into the Nara Visa Truck Terminal where they had the parts on hand to get us rolling again. 

Lots of ghosts on these old roads. Smile and wave.

I’m sharing more from the magical rolls of Rollei CR200 I shot on the Fall 2022 road trip. As unlikely as it seems for people like me who assumed that the film expiration date was tied to its date of manufacture, that is not true. The clock starts ticking when the mother rolls are pulled from cold storage for packaging. Rollei CR200, Rollei Crossbird, and Lomography Peacock all were made in 2005 as AGFA Aviphot Chrome. I like the results this film gives me when it’s behaving well, so I really wanted to believe it was still being made. The answer is NOPE! 

The combination of blue-green deep shadows, magenta shadows, and warm high tones combined with the sharp contrast and narrow latitude of transparency film gives this stock a one of a kind look. When it’s all gone I am going to try to make a Fujifilm film preset for it. I don’t expect great success but if any digital camera system has a shot at consistently delivering the look of an unusual film stock, my money is on Fuji GF/GFX.

There’s been tons written about the specs of this camera. There’s been tons of material written about film versus digital. I can’t speak for anyone else. I’m shooting for a result, and the gear’s job is to let me get there hassle free as possible.

The Spirit of Radio⚡️

Out of bed at 6:00 AM. Rolling towards De Anza by 6:10. The damage: one roll Velvia 50 120. One roll Ektachrome 100 120. And a whole bunch of quantum tunneling in the flash cards of the GFX100S as the scene before me changed with every tick of the clock. Can’t wait to develop the film, process the digital shots, and put that printer to work! I didn’t do my usual practice of shooting with everything I had. The light was changing too fast, and I knew that Ektachrome and Velvia would represent film at its best. I’d have liked to shot Ektar and Pro400H too, but I wasn’t kidding about the light: when mountains are on the horizon things change dramatically during sunrise/sunset. The show peaked about five minutes into the shoot. 10 minutes later it was over. When I had enough light to do film justice I banged off the rolls I had waiting in the two GW690s. Then back to digital. If tomorrow’s weather forecast was better I’d stay another day and revisit this with more film formats. But tomorrow morning promises to be wet and miserable. So: this was it. Make it count. 

On a side note I have not visited Central Avenue since December 2015, next to the last day of Kurt’s Camera being open. In 2015 things did not look good for all of the independent businesses along the route. We were all wondering how they would survive the construction with the massive traffic disruptions that came with it. Looking at the place now I can honestly say Central Avenue has never looked more vibrant and alive. There’s freshly restored neon in place. Old signs have been dusted off and restored. Brand new neon has gone up. Not LED. NEON! And most important, there’s a huge variety of independent businesses up and down the street. There’s no way I would have said this in 2015 but in retrospect the ART project (not the BYD build your disaster buses, but the project itself) might have actually saved Central. Yeah. I never thought I’d say that, either. I’m happy to be wrong, and ecstatic that Central seems to be doing quite well.

Live Life Colorfully! 

Hotel Zazz
In Albuquerque’s Nob Hill neighborhood.

In the heyday of Route 66 this place was a Travelodge. There is a ghost sign referencing it just off interstate 25 south of Albuquerque. 

It’s visible in Ernst Haas’ masterpiece 1969 Central Ave. shot. After his estate decided to pull the licenses on virtually every reproduction of his original photo I decided to re-create my own version. That was back in 2011 when this motel was signed University Lodge. 

I had avoided the eastern half of Central Avenue after 2016, mostly because I was afraid of what I might find up there. Losing Kurt’s Camera was a big blow, and I could easily imagine all of the locally owned businesses going under during construction of the A.R.T. project. Revisiting in 2022 I was pleasantly surprised to see the locally owned businesses thriving amidst a sea of newly restored and brand new neon signage. Neon signage is a big deal to me because in my mind it *defines* Route 66. In the 1950s and 60s main streets of every medium sized town had a collection of glowing electric rainbows. Large cities had miles of neon tubing. 

Starting in the 1970s with ill advised urban renewal programs the neon was seen as ugly and tacky and many towns passed ordinances against it. It would stay in decline for decades along with our willingness to have actual color in commercial architecture. I’m looking forward to giving this place a try soon. Those brilliant colors against the clean white background speak to me in a way the entire the entire Sherwin Williams 100 shades of gray will never match! Let’s hope we can leave the drab and boring monotones behind for the 2020s, our eyes can perceive millions of shades of color, it’s a shame to assault them with monotones🌈

Rollei Retro 80S plus a number 26 ruby red filter: more fun with near infrared film. I like this stuff so much I ordered 10 rolls of Rollei Superpan 200, another extended red sensitivity film. 

It’s not obvious, but regular old silver halide is most sensitive to blue light. Dyes have to be added to make the film respond to greens and reds. Such films are called orthochromatic and panchromatic, respectively. Extended red sensitive films take panchromatic films a bit deeper into the red spectrum, reaching out to about 750nm. For reference, a deep red LED used as part of a cluster in a horticultural lamp peaks at around 660nm. A red LED traffic light typically peaks at 620-630nm. By attenuating colors other than red with the use of the #26 filter, the film delivers stark, high contrast images with blues trending black and anything reflecting IR light practically jumping off the screen: like Geronimo’s Castle, seen here.

Back up your photos, people! Hard drives gonna hard drive, and even if they don’t fail, other things can. 

I didn’t lose anything. On import to LR I use the “copy on import” option to make sure I have a hot backup. If you’re doing this, make sure you point LR to a separate physical drive. Backups to the same device don’t count. 2nd copy gives me my working copy and a hot backup. Second thing I do is run a scheduled weekly file sync of the working drive to yet another drive, in an external drive array. Third level is to use Teracopy plus validate to sync my working drive to a 20TB external drive, which is locked up at work. Once a month I take it home and sync it. 

So what happened? I was using Cineraid external arrays set up as “just a bunch of disks.” I had a SyncFolder backup to an 18TB WD data center drive in the Cineraid. It had been working fine for almost a year. Until it wasn’t. Zero warning, Windows popped an unpartioned drive message, what did I wish to do? YIPE!!! The Cineraid box ate my partition! This triggered a bunch of upgrades to my computing gear, and is why I’ve been a ghost here. As part of that I learned that the Cineraid boxes (purchased as late as 2020 and definitely not cheap) had 2010 era chipsets! USB3 to SATA2 (!), and no support for SAS over USB! WTF, no wonder performance was so bad. Worse, I had uncovered a bug in the hardware with a hard drive way too big for the chipset. To cap off this already long story, the external box was upgraded to a unit supporting USB 3.2 gen2. I knew that would get me a recent chipset. There’s really no other way to tell, all external HD boxes look nice and pretty on the outside. Second thing: I finally began outfitting my photo deep freeze: a server running TrueNAS Scale and ZFS. I should’ve done this ages ago. I have 25 years and 16TB (and counting) of digital assets to preserve. Maybe your solution doesn’t have to be this elaborate, but at least go out to Costco or Best Buy and get yourself an external hard drive. And use it!!! #teracopy #signgeeks #filmphotography

Extended range deeeeeep red IR films have become one of my new obsessions. When out in the desert with our favorite fusion generator cranking rays, slipping the red filter into place cuts the blues and greens sharply. But anything from yellow to near-IR makes a dramatic impression on those little silver halide crystals. I don’t even have to play any games during negative to positive conversion to get this result. The negatives come out with black areas (you know, the ones that make those dramatic whites in the final image?) looking almost like the deep blacks that made Velvia famous. Inverting to positive is a straightforward process. As long as whatever gadget you’re digitizing with can peer into those deep black areas and resolve tonal variations, this film will blow your mind. That makes it a perfect candidate for shooting neon signs at night, because the film is able to pile on density to the glowing tube areas, making them stand out distinctly from the lettering behind the tubes. I like that look a whole lot better than when film (or scanner, more often than you might expect!) throws up its electronic hands and renders the tubes and lettering as an amorphous blob.

A totally unscientific comparison for World Photography Day: Camera scanning, Sony A7Riv VS Fuji GFX100S. 

I used a test shot from my Holga Panoramic 120. So, don’t bother comparing sharpness. There isn’t any! I was looking for color and tonality differences. Besides, the merciless compression on this platform means I could have digitized with my old iPhone 6 and you’d never see any difference in detail. You only need the big numbers if you’re printing or archiving. 

Software was #negativelabpro3.02. Default settings were used for both shots. I see a slightly brighter rendition with the Fuji. Tonality on my film hauler truck shows the Fuji maybe biased a tiny bit green? Just like real Fuji film I guess. My take: the Fuji makes sense for digitizing 4x5. Otherwise, I think it’s too close to call. The Sony does have one maddening trait which you can maybe see in the corners? For some film from certain cameras, the corners vignette too much. But it’s not what you think. Remember, we are flipping negative to positive. I think the automatic lens correction is overdoing the compensation on the corners. Which makes them too dark when flipped to positive. There isn’t a good way to shut this off and make it stick. The Fuji does auto corrections too. All new cameras do. But I’m using manual glass on the Fuji. So the camera has no idea what to do to “help” me. 

The real takeaway? How about that Holga casual sharpness!!! The stuff dreams are made of.

I’m a color film fanatic. Color: from my early childhood obsession with neon signs to the psychedelic fluorescent posters aglow in the “black light cave” at the back of Spencer Gifts in Springfield MO’s Battlefield Mall, if it plugged in and lit up in color, I was enthralled. We won’t even get into the story of little Timmy demonstrating to his neighborhood friends that a bar magnet 🧲 up against the screen of Dad’s new 25 inch color console TV created wild rainbow patterns as the magnet steered the electron beams off their intended course, so that, say, the output meant for the red phosphor hit the blue one instead, making crazy color patterns on the old tube 📺 🙀! Yep. That experiment really impressed mom and dad!

It was always about color. Today, instead of admiring art best left on the walls of the old double wide at the trailer park, or temporarily sending the parents’ expensive entertainment box on a trip to the dark side of the moon, I’m all over color film. Especially transparencies. And cranking out big prints. All in living color. 

There is one type of black and white film that almost gives me the same rush, though. Extended red sensitive “near IR” films teamed with a Wratten 26 ruby red filter. I’m not into subtle. Subtlety has its place. Just not around *my* place! I want my B&W images to leap off the page and smack the viewer’s retinas—this combo gives me that look. And it’s cheap, too! FPP Let It Snow is nice and clean without the filter. With the filter and a two stop EV increase for the filter loss, it gives results like this. I’m still looking for a 120 that will give me similar results. I have experimented with Rollei Retro 80s and Retro 200. Ilford IR. And a few others. Close—but nothing like this stock. I’ll keep trying.

July 2018. 

As we were setting up our respective tripods and cameras, the caretaker came out and struck up a conversation. He was a nice guy, so it was actually a pleasant exchange, but he did say that the property was in the process of renovation. Uh-oh. There’s two kinds of renovation. There’s the kind that honors the history of the place and attempts to build on and preserve all of the elements that make it a survivor. And then there’s the kind of renovation that involves heading out to the home improvement store, getting the lowest bid builder grade stuff one can lay hands on, and absolutely butchering all of the historic elements. I’ll give you one guess which direction this place went.

I honestly don’t know what the answer is. And the truth is there is no one size fits all answer for places like this. It dates to 1949 when it opened as a luxury motor court, it’s on Route 66, and both of these things should elevate it above the run of the male status, but there were so many of these places in Albuquerque.

With luck you get a sustainable rehab in the form of a conversion to affordable housing with the signage and other historical elements restored to their glory days. But it can’t be done for every property and I guess when the lottery numbers were picked, this place did not get the loving restoration treatment it deserves. I know I’m not practical. I’m the guy who wants to rescue every single stray dog and cat I see out on the streets. Obviously that can’t be done either, I guess the best thing to do is remember what it was through photos, and this place had the bones to make it a genuine Route 66 classic.

overall, nothing beats, having a thriving business occupied a historic location, so the best thing you and I as individuals can do is be sure to support these places at every opportunity. To that end I will be spending five days in Cuba, Missouri at Connie’s Wagon Wheel, using it as a sort of bass camp while I explore a part of my state that I have not spent enough time in in the past.

to all the businesses out there fighting to survive on 66 and elsewhere, thank you for keeping it lit, you are appreciated.

Polaroid. The images cost about two dollars a pop, the colors are only casually related to reality, and yet there is something magical about the format that makes me very glad that the film is still available.

I was replying to a question from  @matthewehrmann about why I chose the much less practical two door version of the Bronco over the four-door version. He guessed correctly, it’s because the two-door screams 1966 to me. That morphed into the conversation about why I put up with the admitted pain in the ass that is film photography when I have digital options famous photographers of the 50s and 60s would’ve killed for.

Here is part of the reply, cut down and paraphrased, why I still shoot Polaroid film and film in general  even in 2023:

“…,,,,there’s something magical about capturing those photons in silver halide. Or maybe I’m just getting old, I don’t know. But I really feel it especially with Polaroid of all things. The color fidelity sucks out loud, the dynamic range is worse than a 2008 era smart phone camera, and yet there’s something so tactile about having a one of a kind print in your hand that was formed by the light which hit the very piece of film at the moment that exposure was made. It cannot be re-created, it’s an original. In these days of mass produced everything, having a one of a kind anything is special enough for me to pay the freight on the film costs.”

Getting ready to say “until next time, Connie!” People who pour their hearts, souls and bank accounts into preserving these places are heroes as far as I’m concerned. It is definitely a leap of faith, taking on a place like this, and she has turned it from an eyesore into a destination. I will be cutting down on my Camera packing habits, it’s not like packing the F150, where I just throw stuff in the tote bin and not worry about it. I’ve got a stack of shirts I haven’t even worn yet because how about that? Turns out you can wear a shirt two or three days in a row on the road and nobody will notice or care. And I’m sure not out to impress anyone when I’m in road trip mode!  I do have the essentials. Lotsa film. Lotsa cameras. Fresh copies of @mcjerry66’s indispensable travel guide because guess what? I don’t really know Missouri Route 66 that well at least not in the eastern half of the state. And I needed to pick up the latest from gentleman @jimhinckley. I could’ve ordered both of these from Amazon, but I would much rather buy them at a place like this. It is after all our financial inputs that keep the lights on at places like this, so if you love them, patronize them.

Until next time, @echolswagonwheel !

Until you’ve heard the Stones do it live you haven’t heard it. It was while auditioning this song cranked up to 11 on my 1975 Marantz 2325 receiver I had set up in the projection booth of the drive-in theater, where I was still running the movies every night, Well, that is when I figured out that Missouri 96 had to be The Mother Road. Call it Rollei CR200. Crossbird. Lomo Peacock. I’ve enjoyed this film under all those names. In every format from 110 to 120 including a batch of 127 Rerachrome. 127? It was darling of the tourist trap prepackaged slide industry. Same width as 35mm, but most cameras shot almost square frames, with no sprocket holes. 

When it’s developed as a transparency in E6, the images have a deep aqua base tint which transitions to magenta as the exposure values approach 18%. Bright details show colors shifted to warm yellows. Split toning, all done in chemistry. Cross processed in C41 I get stunning purple negatives which #negativelabpro inverts to a riot of teal and orange. There is *nothing* else like this film. 

Turns out it was last made in 2005. I discovered it as Lomo Peacock in 2012. Then, as Rollei CR200. There were all sorts of rumors surrounding this film, chief among them that it was a Belgian made derivative of AGFA RSX, a beautiful and well respected transparency film from the grand old German company. Except: no. I have some original AGFA except it’s the consumer version: 2001 vintage Precisa CT100. Examples are in my feed. Even 20 years after its expiration date it looks great. But it isn’t CR200.

The films are radically dissimilar.  One rumor was that the CR films originated from a contaminated batch of late production RSX. Wait. One of my favorite films was the spawn of an industrial accident? Hard NO.  I refused to believe it. My best argument against the single batch origin was that during the 2010s the film sold out every year, reappearing the next year with expiry dates incremented. So, that’s proof, right? We can’t be picking film off a carcass, right? RIGHT? Err….Hold that thought. See you in the comments. #rollei #shootfilm @flagstaffcamera Matt ought to enjoy this twisted tale!

Fuji’s greatest parlor trick lies in their application of a film transfer function database created decades ago during the development of what would become the Fuji Frontier minilab system. 

transfer functions are nothing more than mathematical models describing the behavior of a linear system. Putting it as simply as I can put it, information is fed into a system which provides the resources necessary to allow that transfer function to modify the original data into something new and unique. 

in this case, the information is supplied by the image sensor in the camera and the transfer function models the behavior of Fuji Velvia 50 transparency film.

Because Fuji did such a thorough job modeling the behavior of all of these different films back in the 1980s and 1990s, a photographer today can experience the look and feel of processes that have not been manufactured for decades.

Now, a cynic might point out that Fuji themselves are responsible for ending production of a great deal of those legendary film stocks. That’s a matter of record, but the regulatory environment as well as the market itself has shifted dramatically since 1999. Even if Fuji found a way to re-engineer those formulas to comply with things like the RoHS directive, compliance would make the product so expensive no one could afford it, and then we would all be complaining about that.

Consider this: a couple years ago we couldn’t even manage to keep the store shelves stocked with toilet paper. I think we can agree that color photographic film is at least slightly more complex than butt paper! Makin’ stuff is hard!

I will continue to enjoy color photographic film as long as it survives, but I’m also grateful Fuji found a way to give all of that transfer function research new life in their digital cameras.
